_refine_special_details
;
The crystal under investigation was found to be non-merohedrally 
twinned. The orientation matrices for the two components were 
identified using the program Cell_Now, with the two components 
being related by a 180 degree rotation around the real b-axis 
or the reciprocal axis 0 -4 1. Due to the large unit cell size 
and twinning the crystal to detector distance was extended to 
allow for better peak separation (from the default 3.7 cm to 
9 cm). The two components were initially integrated using Saint, 
but integration proofed problematic due to excessive multiple 
overlap of reflections, resulting in large numbers of rejected 
reflections. 

Attempts were made to adjust integration parameters to avoid 
excessive rejections (through adjustments to integration queue 
size, blending of profiles, integration box slicing and twin 
overlap parameters). This and omitting integration box size 
refinement led to substantially lower numbers of rejections, 
but the data that could be obtained this way were still highly 
incomplete, and of substantially lower quality than an approach 
without simultaneous integration of both twin domains (see below).

With no complete and acceptable quality data set obtainable through 
simultaneous integration of both twin domains, the data were instead 
handled as if not twinned, with only the major domain integrated, 
and converted into an hklf 5 type format hkl file after integration 
using the "Make HKLF5 File" routine as implemented in WinGX. The 
twin law matrix was used as follows: 

180.0 degree rotation about   0.  1.  0. direct lattice direction:
[  -1.000    0.003    0.000]
[   0.000    1.000    0.000]
[   0.000    0.499   -1.000]
Figure of merit =   1.75 ***********


The Overlap R1 and R2 values used were 0.15, i.e. reflections with 
a discriminator function less or equal to overlap radius of 0.32 
were counted overlapped, all others as single. The discriminator 
function used was the "delta function on index non-integrality". No 
reflections were omitted.

The structure was solved using direct methods with the uncorrected 
hklf 4 type file and was refined using the WinGX created hklf 5 type 
file, resulting in a BASF value of 0.261(5).

No Rint value is obtainable for the hklf 5 type file using the WinGX
routine. 

The structure exhibits pseudo-translational symmetry and is 
commensurately modulated by unit cell doubling along the b-axis 
direction. Exact translational symmetry is broken by modulation of 
lead-iodide units (especially the lead ions) that also induces 
modulation of the ethyl ammonium moieties. The remainder of the 
organic ligands obeys translational symmetry along the b-axis 
direction. 

The structure was refined without use of constraints or restraints 
for non-hydrogen atoms. No restraints for thermal parameters were 
used. 
;
